<p>To install these, create a browser bookmark whose "location" is that long nasty <code>javascript:</code> URL. The way you do this depends on your browser. Some notable approaches:</p>

<h3>In Most Desktop Browsers</h3>

<p>You usually want these on the toolbar or in the menu, so they're easily accessible.</p>

<ol>
<li>Go into the "view" menu and make sure the "bookmark toolbar" is visible, or else open your browser's bookmark manager.</li>
<li>Drag the bookmarklet links and drop them where you want them.</li>
</ol>

<h3>On iOS Safari</h3>

<p>You usually want these at the top of the "favorites" section of your bookmarks. That way, you can activate them by tapping on the URL bar and then choosing the appropriate icon.</p>

<p>Safari doesn't want you to bookmark javascript URLs by accident, so it adds an extra step: you have to create a normal bookmark, then manually replace its URL. In more detail:</p>

<ol>
<li>First, use the share menu to bookmark <em>this</em> page. Put it in the "favorites" section.</li>
<li>Copy the <code>javascript:</code> URL to the clipboard. (On iOS ‚â• 13 you can tap-and-hold the links; on iOS ‚â§ 12 you have to copy from the textarea.)</li>
<li>Open your bookmarks and tap "edit".</li>
<li>Tap the bookmark you just made. Rename it, and replace the current URL with the <code>javascript:</code> URL.</li>
</ol>
